description: From Middle English kemben, from Old English cemban, from Proto-West Germanic *kambijan, from Proto-Germanic *kambijaną (“to comb”). Cognate with Dutch kemmen (“to comb”), German kämmen (“to comb”), Icelandic kemba (“to comb; card; debug”).

verbs.description: kemb (third-person singular simple present kembs, present participle kembing, simple past and past participle kembed or kempt)
